    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Can Blacks Afford Not to Vote?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Venkat Sampath letter asks how blacks can question Sen Joseph Lieberman's commitment to racial equality, given that Lieberman courageously went to South to register black voters in 1960's (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Why Blacks Doubt Lieberman'' (Op-Ed, Aug. 17):</p>
        <p>I cannot understand how blacks can question Senator Joseph I. Lieberman's commitment to racial equality, progress and the prosperity of African-Americans. This is the man who courageously went to the South in the 1960's to register black voters not because it would look good on his political resume but because it was the right thing to do.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Why Blacks Doubt Lieberman'' (Op-Ed, Aug. 17):</p>
        <p>I cannot understand how blacks can question Senator Joseph I. Lieberman's commitment to racial equality, progress and the prosperity of African-Americans. This is the man who courageously went to the South in the 1960's to register black voters not because it would look good on his political resume but because it was the right thing to do.</p>
        <p>Yes, there are some differences in the way Mr. Lieberman would approach affirmative action, but that should not hold back blacks from supporting him.</p>
        <p>VENKAT SAMPATH  Westport, Conn., Aug. 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
